[30;1m28 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m29 | [0m[35m    The process starts by tokenizing the text into pseudosentences of[0m
[30;1m30 | [0m[35m    a fixed size w. Then, depending on the method used, similarity[0m
[30;1m31 | [0m[35m    scores are assigned at sentence gaps. The algorithm proceeds by[0m
[30;1m32 | [0m[35m    detecting the peak differences between these scores and marking[0m
[30;1m33 | [0m[35m    them as boundaries. The boundaries are normalized to the closest[0m
[30;1m34 | [0m[35m    paragraph break and the segmented text is returned.[0m

[30;1m2160 | [0m[35msingle character, then that byte string is stored in an internal[0m
[30;1m2161 | [0m[35mbuffer, and re-used on the next call to ``read()``.  However, if the[0m
[30;1m2162 | [0m[35msize argument is too small to read even a single character, even[0m
[30;1m2163 | [0m[35mthough at least one character is available, then the ``read()`` method[0m
[30;1m2164 | [0m[35mwill read additional bytes until it can return a single character.[0m
[30;1m2165 | [0m[35mThis ensures that the ``read()`` method does not return an empty[0m
[30;1m2166 | [0m[35mstring, which could be mistaken for indicating the end of the file.[0m

[30;1m244 | [0m[35m        Returns the log-probability of the given symbol sequence. If the[0m
[30;1m245 | [0m[35m        sequence is labelled, then returns the joint log-probability of the[0m
[30;1m246 | [0m[35m        symbol, state sequence. Otherwise, uses the forward algorithm to find[0m

[30;1m229 | [0m[35m        Returns the probability of the given symbol sequence. If the sequence[0m

[30;1m20 | [0m[35ma probabilistic function of the state. HMMs share the Markov chain's[0m
[30;1m21 | [0m[35massumption, being that the probability of transition from one state to another[0m
[30;1m22 | [0m[35monly depends on the current state - i.e. the series of states that led to the[0m
[30;1m23 | [0m[35mcurrent state are not used. They are also time invariant.[0m
[30;1m24 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m25 | [0m[35mThe HMM is a directed graph, with probability weighted edges (representing the[0m
[30;1m26 | [0m[35mprobability of a transition between the source and sink states) where each[0m

[30;1m15 | [0m[35ma bottom-up chart parser for ``PCFG`` grammars.  It maintains a queue of edges,[0m
[30;1m16 | [0m[35mand adds them to the chart one at a time.  The ordering of this queue[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35mis based on the probabilities associated with the edges, allowing the[0m
[30;1m18 | [0m[35mparser to expand more likely edges before less likely ones.  Each[0m
[30;1m19 | [0m[35msubclass implements a different queue ordering, producing different[0m
[30;1m20 | [0m[35msearch strategies.  Currently the following subclasses are defined:[0m

[30;1m703 | [0m[35mHowever, even after discarding the infinite cycles, some trees can remain[0m
[30;1m704 | [0m[35mintractable, due to combinatorial explosion in a relation. This happens in[0m
[30;1m705 | [0m[35mWordNet, because the ``also_sees()`` relation has a big Strongly Connected[0m
[30;1m706 | [0m[35mComponent (_SCC_) consisting in 758 synsets, where any member node is[0m
[30;1m707 | [0m[35mtransitively connected by the same relation, to all other members of the[0m
[30;1m708 | [0m[35msame SCC. This produces intractable relation trees for each of these 758[0m
[30;1m709 | [0m[35msynsets, i. e. trees that are too big to compute or display on any computer.[0m

[30;1m119 | [0m[35m        constituents = {}[0m

[30;1m33 | [0m[35m    tree.  Each ``TreeSegmentWidget`` connects a single "node widget"[0m
[30;1m34 | [0m[35m    to a sequence of zero or more "subtree widgets".  By default, the[0m
[30;1m35 | [0m[35m    bottom of the node is connected to the top of each subtree by a[0m
[30;1m36 | [0m[35m    single line.  However, if the ``roof`` attribute is set, then a[0m
[30;1m37 | [0m[35m    single triangular "roof" will connect the node to all of its[0m
[30;1m38 | [0m[35m    children.[0m

[30;1m38 | [0m[35mGrammar productions are implemented by the ``Production`` class.[0m
[30;1m39 | [0m[35mEach ``Production`` consists of a left hand side and a right hand[0m

[30;1m599 | [0m[35m    """[0m
[30;1m600 | [0m[35m    :param tree: the tree root[0m
[30;1m601 | [0m[35m    :param children: a function taking as argument a tree node[0m
[30;1m602 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m603 | [0m[35m            Output a dictionary representing a Minimum Spanning Tree (MST)[0m

[30;1m79 | [0m[35m    A graphical tool for exploring the recursive descent parser.  The tool[0m
[30;1m80 | [0m[35m    displays the parser's tree and the remaining text, and allows the[0m
[30;1m81 | [0m[35m    user to control the parser's operation.  In particular, the user[0m
[30;1m82 | [0m[35m    can expand subtrees on the frontier, match tokens on the frontier[0m
[30;1m83 | [0m[35m    against the text, and backtrack.  A "step" button simply steps[0m
[30;1m84 | [0m[35m    through the parsing process, performing the operations that[0m
[30;1m85 | [0m[35m    ``RecursiveDescentParser`` would use.[0m

[30;1m47 | [0m[35m 2. Parent Annotation[0m
[30;1m48 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m49 | [0m[35m    In addition to binarizing the tree, there are two standard[0m
[30;1m50 | [0m[35m    modifications to node labels we can do in the same traversal: parent[0m
[30;1m51 | [0m[35m    annotation and Markov order-N smoothing (or sibling smoothing).[0m
[30;1m52 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m53 | [0m[35m    The purpose of parent annotation is to refine the probabilities of[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2560[0m[34m of [0m[33m2590[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m

   Pattern: [32m\s(apt|apt\-get|aria2c|arp|ash|awk|base64|bash|bpftrace|busybox|cat|chmod|chown|cp|cpan|cpulimit|crontab|csh|curl|cut|dash|dd|diff|dmesg|dmsetup|dnf|docker|dpkg|easy_install|ed|emacs|env|expand|expect|facter|find|finger|flock|fmt|ftp|gawk|gdb|gimp|git|grep|head|iftop|ionice|ip|irb|jjs|journalctl|jrunscript|ksh|ld\.so|ldconfig|logsave|ltrace|lua|mail|mawk|mount|mtr|mv|mysql|nano|nawk|nc|nice|nl|nmap|node|od|openssl|perl|pg|php|pic|pico|pip|puppet|readelf|red|rlogin|rlwrap|rpm|rpmquery|rsync|ruby|run\-mailcap|run\-parts|rvim|scp|screen|script|sed|service|setarch|sftp|shuf|smbclient|socat|sort|sqlite3|ssh|start\-stop\-daemon|stdbuf|strace|systemctl|tail|tar|taskset|tclsh|tcpdump|tee|telnet|tftp|time|timeout|tmux|top|ul|unexpand|uniq|unshare|vi|vim|watch|wget|whois|wish|xargs|xxd|yum|zsh|zypper)\s[0m
[30;1m28 | [0m[35m    subtree is the head (left hand side) of the production and all of[0m
[30;1m29 | [0m[35m    its children are the right hand side constituents.  In order to[0m
[30;1m30 | [0m[35m    convert a tree into CNF, we simply need to ensure that every subtree[0m
[30;1m31 | [0m[35m    has either two subtrees as children (binarization), or one leaf node[0m
[30;1m32 | [0m[35m    (non-terminal).  In order to binarize a subtree with more than two[0m
[30;1m33 | [0m[35m    children, we must introduce artificial nodes.[0m
[30;1m34 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m35 | [0m[35m    There are two popular methods to convert a tree into CNF: left[0m
